Much like the {{ill|Katsugun Jizō Bosatsu|ja|勝軍地蔵菩薩}} enshrined on {{ill|Atago Mountain (Kyoto)|ja|愛宕山 (京都市)|lt=Atago Mountain|lt_ja=愛宕山}} in Kyoto, the Kagami Rock (also referred to as Kagamaseki) at the Suzuka Pass—regarded as an iwasaka ({{ill|Iwasaka|ja|磐座}})—lies on the boundary between Kyoto ({{ill|Kyoto|ja|京都|lt=Kyoto|lt_ja=京}}) and Tanba ({{ill|Tanba Province|ja|丹波国|lt=Tanba|lt_ja=丹波}}). There, by enshrining General Tamura within the rock, he was revered as a “general Jizō” in tandem with Suzuka Gongen, evidencing an ancient faith in Saino no Kami ({{ill|Saino no Kami|ja|塞の神}}). This belief later evolved into the legend of Sakanoue no Tamuramaro, as recounted in otogi-zōshi such as ‘Suzuka no Sōshi’ and ‘Standing Eboshi’, as well as in the {{ill|Okujōruri|ja|奥浄瑠璃}} text ‘Tamura Sandai-ki’, which narrates the tale of General Tamura and Suzuka Gomen as a divine couple battling the demon god ({{ill|Oodakemaru|ja|大嶽丸|lt=Demon God|lt_ja=鬼神}}). {{Sfn|阿部|2004|pages=88-93}}

In the Shintō collection (‘{{ill|Shintō Shū|ja|神道集}}’), it is recorded that “the parents of Kakuwa-dono were also taught the principles of Shintō, and became the Suzuka Daimyōjin of the Iga Province Sannomiya”; however, since the Iga Sannomiya is identified with {{ill|Hataki Shrine|ja|波多岐神社}}, this is suspected to be a misprint for the Ise Province Sannomiya. {{Refnest|group=注|『神道集』「児持山大明神の事」}}

During the {{ill|Edo Period|ja|江戸時代}}, the published work ‘{{ill|Ise Grand Shrine Famous Places Illustrated|ja|伊勢参宮名所図会}}’ in its “Suzuka Mountain” section depicts, separated by the Kagami Rock of the Suzuka Pass, a bolded “Suzuka Shrine” on the Ise side and, on the Ōmi side, a Tamura Myōjin (a shrine distinct from {{ill|Tamura Shrine (Kōka)|ja|田村神社 (甲賀市)}}), with an accompanying explanation stating that Suzuka Shrine was also known by alternate names such as Katayama Shrine and the bolded “Prefectural Shrine”. {{Sfn|桐村|2012|pages=117-121}}

An inscribed stone pillar at the ruins of Tamura Shrine records that in the 40th year of the Meiji Era (1907) it was merged into Katayama Shrine; thus, the Tamura Shrine known as Tamura Myōjin during the Edo Period was incorporated into Katayama Shrine. {{Sfn|桐村|2012|pages=117-121}}

In the 11th year of the Heisei Era (1999), the main hall was burned down due to arson.

== Landmarks and Historic Sites ==
* Kagami Rock of Suzuka Mountain (Kagamaseki, Kagamihada)
* The ruins of Tamura Shrine (also known as Tamura Hory or Tamura Myōjin)
*: It is said that when Sakanoue no Tamuramaro deposited his bows and arrows ({{ill|Bows and Arrows|ja|弓箭}}), {{ill|Fumimuro Watamaro|ja|文室綿麻呂}} built a hall at that spot. {{Refnest|group=注|『三國地誌』巻之二十三 伊勢國 鈴鹿郡 神祠}}
* The remains of the shrine festival site at Suzuka Pass

