[[File:Katayama shrine from Tōkaidō meisho zue.png|サムネイル|250px|right|東海道名所図会「鈴鹿社」]]

'''Katayama Shrine''' (片山神社) is a {{ill|Shinto Shrine|ja|神社}} classified as a {{ill|Shikinaisha|ja|式内社}} located at Sakasita 636, {{ill|Seki Town|ja|関町}}, {{ill|Kameyama City|ja|亀山市}}, {{ill|Mie Prefecture|ja|三重県}}.

== Overview ==
It is situated on the {{ill|Suzuka Tunnel|ja|鈴鹿トンネル}} of {{ill|National Route 1|ja|国道1号}}, which forms part of the border ({{ill|Prefectural Border|ja|県境}}) between {{ill|Shiga Prefecture|ja|滋賀県}} and {{ill|Mie Prefecture|ja|三重県}}, atop the {{ill|Suzuka Pass|ja|鈴鹿峠}} from which one can overlook both the {{ill|Suzuka River|ja|鈴鹿川}} flowing toward {{ill|Ise Bay|ja|伊勢湾}} and the {{ill|Tamura River|ja|田村川}} flowing from {{ill|Lake Biwa|ja|琵琶湖}}. {{Sfn|阿部|2004|pages=88-93}}{{Sfn|桐村|2012|pages=117-121}}

The surrounding area is a sacred land blessed with abundant water. It is renowned as the site of the Suzuka Misogi, where the Saio ({{ill|Saio|ja|斎王}}) en route to {{ill|Ise Grand Shrine|ja|伊勢神宮}} once stayed to perform misogi ({{ill|Misogi|ja|禊}}), and later became consecrated by shamanic practitioners ({{ill|Shamanic Practitioner|ja|巫覡}}) performing purification rituals ({{ill|Purification Ritual|ja|祓え}}). 

Within the precincts stand the monument commemorating the origin of Suzuka-ryu naginatajutsu – {{ill|Suzuka-ryu|ja|鈴鹿流|lt=Suzuka-ryu Naginatajutsu Origin|lt_ja=鈴鹿流薙刀術発生之地}} – and a monument honoring the filial piety of Bankichi.

== Deities ==
; Main Deity
* {{ill|Yamato-hime-no-mikoto|ja|倭姫命|lt=Yamato-hime-no-mikoto|lt_ja=倭比賣命}}

; Enshrined Deities
* {{ill|Seoritsu-hime|ja|瀬織津姫|lt=Seoritsu-hime|lt_ja=瀬織津比売神}}
* {{ill|Kibikido-nushi-no-kami|ja|気吹戸主神|lt=Kibikido-nushi-no-kami|lt_ja=氣吹戸主神}}
* {{ill|Hayasasurabime-no-kami|ja|速佐須良比売神}}
* {{ill|Sakanoue no Tamuramaro|ja|坂上田村麻呂|lt=Sakanoue no Tamuramaro|lt_ja=坂上田村麿}}
* {{ill|Amaterasu|ja|天照大神}}
* {{ill|Susanoo-no-Mikoto|ja|速須佐之男命}}
* {{ill|Ichikishimahime-no-mikoto|ja|市杵島姫命}}
* {{ill|Ooyamazumi-no-kami|ja|大山津見神}}

== History ==
=== Founding ===
The exact founding date is unknown. Originally, the three mountains of Mikoyama ({{ill|Suzuka-dake|ja|鈴鹿嶽}}, {{ill|Takenamada-dake|ja|武名嶽}}, and {{ill|Takahata-dake|ja|高幡嶽}}) located on the eastern side of the Suzuka Pass were revered as a sacred mountain ({{ill|Sacred Mountain|ja|神体山}}). On its central peak, {{ill|Seoritsu-hime|ja|瀬織津姫}} was enshrined, while on the left and right peaks {{ill|Ibuki-do-nushi|ja|伊吹戸主}} and {{ill|Hayasasurahime|ja|速佐須良姫}} were respectively honored. However, a fire caused the transfer of the enshrinement to the old Suzuka Tondo Shrine. Subsequent repeated transfers due to frequent fires led to a unification of the shrine enshrining Yamato-hime – known as the Suzuka Shrine ({{ill|Suzuka Shrine|ja|鈴鹿社}}) – with the four deities, and later five additional deities including {{ill|Sakanoue no Tamuramaro|ja|坂上田村麻呂}} were added. In the 2nd year of the Einin Era ({{ill|Einin Era|ja|永仁}} 2, 1294), the shrine was relocated to the area of Tatsukami Saka and became the guardian shrine of Sakasita-juku ({{ill|Sakasita-juku|ja|坂下宿}}) enshrining Suzuka-hime. In the 40th year of the Meiji Era ({{ill|Meiji Era|ja|明治}} 40, 1907), the Tamura Shrine ({{ill|Tamura Shrine|ja|田村神社}}) near the Kagami Rock of Suzuka Pass was merged, forming the present structure.

