The exact founding date is unknown. Originally, the three mountains of Mikoyama ({{ill|Suzuka-dake|ja|鈴鹿嶽}}, {{ill|Takenamada-dake|ja|武名嶽}}, and {{ill|Takahata-dake|ja|高幡嶽}}) located on the eastern side of the Suzuka Pass were revered as a sacred mountain ({{ill|Sacred Mountain|ja|神体山}}). On its central peak, {{ill|Seoritsu-hime|ja|瀬織津姫}} was enshrined, while on the left and right peaks {{ill|Ibuki-do-nushi|ja|伊吹戸主}} and {{ill|Hayasasurahime|ja|速佐須良姫}} were respectively honored. However, a fire caused the transfer of the enshrinement to the old Suzuka Tondo Shrine. Subsequent repeated transfers due to frequent fires led to a unification of the shrine enshrining Yamato-hime – known as the Suzuka Shrine ({{ill|Suzuka Shrine|ja|鈴鹿社}}) – with the four deities, and later five additional deities including {{ill|Sakanoue no Tamuramaro|ja|坂上田村麻呂}} were added. In the 2nd year of the Einin Era ({{ill|Einin Era|ja|永仁}} 2, 1294), the shrine was relocated to the area of Tatsukami Saka and became the guardian shrine of Sakasita-juku ({{ill|Sakasita-juku|ja|坂下宿}}) enshrining Suzuka-hime. In the 40th year of the Meiji Era ({{ill|Meiji Era|ja|明治}} 40, 1907), the Tamura Shrine ({{ill|Tamura Shrine|ja|田村神社}}) near the Kagami Rock of Suzuka Pass was merged, forming the present structure.

