[[File:Katayama shrine from Tōkaidō meisho zue.png|サムネイル|250px|right|東海道名所図会「鈴鹿社」]]

'''Katayama Shrine''' (片山神社) is a {{ill|Shinto Shrine|ja|神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinto Shrine|qq=}} classified as a {{ill|Shikinaisha|ja|式内社|1=Shikinaisha|2=ja|3=式内社|qq=draft|1=Shikinaisha|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shikinaisha|13=User:Immanuelle/Shikinaisha|qq=}} located at Sakasita 636, {{ill|Seki Town|ja|関町|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Seki Town|qq=}}, {{ill|Kameyama City|ja|亀山市|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kameyama City|qq=}}, {{ill|Mie Prefecture|ja|三重県|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mie Prefecture|qq=}}.

== Overview ==
It is situated on the {{ill|Suzuka Tunnel|ja|鈴鹿トンネル|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Suzuka Tunnel|qq=}} of {{ill|National Route 1|ja|国道1号|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/National Route 1|qq=}}, which forms part of the border ({{ill|Prefectural Border|ja|県境|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Prefectural Border|qq=}}) between {{ill|Shiga Prefecture|ja|滋賀県|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shiga Prefecture|qq=}} and {{ill|Mie Prefecture|ja|三重県|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mie Prefecture|qq=}}, atop the {{ill|Suzuka Pass|ja|鈴鹿峠|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Suzuka Pass|qq=}} from which one can overlook both the {{ill|Suzuka River|ja|鈴鹿川|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Suzuka River|qq=}} flowing toward {{ill|Ise Bay|ja|伊勢湾|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ise Bay|qq=}} and the {{ill|Tamura River|ja|田村川|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tamura River|qq=}} flowing from {{ill|Lake Biwa|ja|琵琶湖|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Lake Biwa|qq=}}. {{Sfn|阿部|2004|pages=88-93}}{{Sfn|桐村|2012|pages=117-121}}

The surrounding area is a sacred land blessed with abundant water. It is renowned as the site of the Suzuka Misogi, where the Saio ({{ill|Saio|ja|斎王|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Saio|qq=}}) en route to {{ill|Ise Grand Shrine|ja|伊勢神宮|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ise Grand Shrine|qq=}} once stayed to perform misogi ({{ill|Misogi|ja|禊|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Misogi|qq=}}), and later became consecrated by shamanic practitioners ({{ill|Shamanic Practitioner|ja|巫覡|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shamanic Practitioner|qq=}}) performing purification rituals ({{ill|Purification Ritual|ja|祓え|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Purification Ritual|qq=}}). 

Within the precincts stand the monument commemorating the origin of Suzuka-ryu naginatajutsu – {{ill|Suzuka-ryu|ja|鈴鹿流|lt=Suzuka-ryu Naginatajutsu Origin|lt_ja=鈴鹿流薙刀術発生之地|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Suzuka-ryu|qq=}} – and a monument honoring the filial piety of Bankichi.

