'''Katayama Shrine''' (片山神社) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|en|Shinto shrine|qid=Q845945|lt=Shinto Shrine|1=Shinto shrine}} classified as a {{ill|Shikinaisha|ja|式内社|1=Shikinaisha|2=ja|3=式内社|1=Shikinaisha|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shikinaisha|13=User:Immanuelle|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|2=ja|3=延喜式神名帳|4=zh|5=延喜式神名帳|6=simple|7=Engishiki Jinmyocho|lt=Shikinaisha}} located at Sakasita 636, {{ill|Seki, Mie|en|Seki, Mie|qid=Q7447180|lt=Seki Town|1=Seki, Mie}}, {{ill|Kameyama, Mie|en|Kameyama, Mie|qid=Q646858|lt=Kameyama City|1=Kameyama, Mie}}, {{ill|Mie Prefecture|en|Mie Prefecture|qid=Q128196|lt=Mie Prefecture|1=Mie Prefecture}}.

== Overview ==
It is situated on the {{ill|Suzuka Tunnel|ja|鈴鹿トンネル|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Suzuka Tunnel|1=Suzuka tunnel (Shin-Meishin Expressway)|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q11649475}} of {{ill|Japan National Route 1|en|Japan National Route 1|qid=Q1191191|lt=National Route 1|1=Japan National Route 1}}, which forms part of the border ({{ill|Prefectural Border|ja|県境|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Prefectural Border|1=prefectural border|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q11582641}}) between {{ill|Shiga Prefecture|en|Shiga Prefecture|qid=Q131358|lt=Shiga Prefecture|1=Shiga Prefecture}} and {{ill|Mie Prefecture|en|Mie Prefecture|qid=Q128196|lt=Mie Prefecture|1=Mie Prefecture}}, atop the {{ill|Suzuka Pass|ja|鈴鹿峠|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Suzuka Pass|1=Suzuka Pass|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q11649485}} from which one can overlook both the {{ill|Suzuka River|en|Suzuka River|qid=Q7651182|lt=Suzuka River|1=Suzuka River}} flowing toward {{ill|Ise Bay|en|Ise Bay|qid=Q1368308|lt=Ise Bay|1=Ise Bay}} and the {{ill|Tamura River|ja|田村川|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tamura River|1=Tamura River|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q17172424}} flowing from {{ill|Lake Biwa|en|Lake Biwa|qid=Q200239|lt=Lake Biwa|1=Lake Biwa}}. {{Sfn|阿部|2004|pages=88-93}}{{Sfn|桐村|2012|pages=117-121}}

The surrounding area is a sacred land blessed with abundant water. It is renowned as the site of the Suzuka Misogi, where the Saio ({{ill|Saiō|en|Saiō|qid=Q19841349|lt=Saio|1=Saiō}}) en route to {{ill|Ise Shrine|en|Ise Shrine|qid=Q687168|lt=Ise Grand Shrine|1=Ise Grand Shrine}} once stayed to perform misogi ({{ill|Misogi|en|Misogi|qid=Q1936265|lt=Misogi|1=Misogi}}), and later became consecrated by shamanic practitioners ({{ill|Shamanic Practitioner|ja|巫覡|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shamanic Practitioner|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 巫|1=Wu (shaman)|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q3687892}}) performing purification rituals ({{ill|Purification Ritual|ja|祓え|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Purification Ritual|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 祓|1=Harae|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q3127244}}). 

Within the precincts stand the monument commemorating the origin of Suzuka-ryu naginatajutsu – {{ill|Suzuka-ryu|ja|鈴鹿流|lt=Suzuka-ryu Naginatajutsu Origin|lt_ja=鈴鹿流薙刀術発生之地|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Suzuka-ryu|1=Suzuka-ryū‎|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q11649496}} – and a monument honoring the filial piety of Bankichi.

